observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:

a. Direct the Inventory Committee to fast-track the completion of the one-time cleansing of PPE following the procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006, to fairly present the PPE balances in the financial statements;

b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to draw necessary correcting entries for the erroneous depreciation;

c. Designate a full-time General Services Officer (GSO) who will be responsible for the preservation, maintenance, and safekeeping of the PPEs of the LGU; and

d. Pending the cleansing of the PPE account, require the municipal accountant and the GSO to maintain separate ledger and property cards and PAR for acquisitions of PPE in C.Y. 2024 onwards, conduct regular reconciliation and physical count.

We commended the Management for its effort to comply with the imposition of mandatory deductions for Pag-IBIG, PhilHealth, and GSIS and remitting the same to the concerned agency within the prescribed period. However, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to trace, insofar as practicable, the unreconciled balance of Due to Pag-ibig amounting to P5,859.41 and draw necessary correcting entry to reflect the adjusted balance;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to withhold from the employees the deficient Pag-Ibig contributions (personal share) and also allocate budget for its corresponding government share for the months February to April 2024 to effect the correct contributions;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to make a formal representation to the nearest PhilHealth Office on the resolution of the unremitted prior year premiums totaling P253,656.74 brought about by the deferment of collection using the 4.5% premium rate where actual remittance made were allegedly based only from 4% premium rate;
Direct the Municipal HRMO to update the GSIS accounts of the employees to conform with their latest employment status, especially on the accurate records of their compensation; and
Direct the HRMO and Municipal Accountant to make a formal representation to the GSIS Office for the reconciliation of their respective records, in case unreconciled balance still persist after compliance on the immediately preceding recommendation.

We recommended that management:

a. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with a monthly report of receivables from market-related operations;

b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the receivables;

c. Direct the Market Supervisor to spearhead the execution of lease contracts on all market stallholders; and

d. Pursue available remedies by the LGU for default under Sections 6B.09 of Municipal Ordinance No. 24 series of 2020 and entertain the possibility of not renewing the business permit of defaulting lessees.

We recommended that management:

Direct the Inventory Committee to fast-track the completion of the one-time cleansing of PPE following the procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006, to fairly present the PPE balances in the financial statements;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to draw necessary correcting entries for the erroneous depreciation;

Designate a full-time General Services Officer (GSO) who will be responsible for the preservation, maintenance, and safekeeping of the PPEs of the LGU; and

Pending the cleansing of the PPE account, require the municipal accountant and the GSO to maintain separate ledger and property cards and PAR for acquisitions of PPE in C.Y. 2024 onwards, conduct regular reconciliation of assets and physical count.

We recommended that management:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with a monthly report of receivables from market-related operations;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the receivables;

Direct the Market Supervisor to spearhead the execution of lease contracts on all market stallholders; and

Pursue available remedies by the LGU for default under Sections 6B.09 of Municipal Ordinance No. 24 series of 2020 and entertain the possibility of not renewing the business permit of defaulting lessees.

We have recommended that the Municipal Engineer submit the Status Report of the projects listed in the Annex of this audit finding and Certificates of Project Completion to the Office of the Municipal Accountant as basis in the transfer of the completed projects under the CIP to its appropriate PPE accounts;
Require the Municipal Accountant to transfer the completed projects recorded under the Trust Fund to the General Fund upon submission of full liquidation to the grantor; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant shall reclassify projects recorded under the CIP to its appropriate PPE account upon completion of the project.

We have recommended that the management enjoin the Acting Municipal Accountant to transfer the unexpended balances of QRF, DRRMF-MOOE and savings from completed projects classified as capital outlay to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability -DRRM” in the Trust Fund books, after updating the LDRRMF utilization report;
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and maintain separate RAAO for QRF, MOOE and CO which shall be reconciled with the accounting records to determine the correct amount to be transferred to the Trust Fund books; and
Require the LDRRM Council to incorporate a separate caption in the Annual LDRRMF Investment Plan, the programs/projects/activities of the unexpended balances of prior years to maximize its use for speedy realization of the LDRRM objectives.

We have recommended that management require the department concerned to submit the list of all ongoing government projects/programs/activities and those that are to be implemented during the year;
Inform the audit team within ten (10) days after award of the infrastructure      project or before the start of the program/activity that the project signboard and/or public notices are posted; and
Require the department concerned to strictly submit the Quarterly Report on Publicized Government Projects/Programs/Activity at the end of each quarter.

We have recommended that management:

Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee to ensure completeness of the required supporting documentary requirements for all contracts submitted for review in accordance with COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated
 February 12, 2009 and COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 12, 2012;

Require the personnel in-charge in the submission of the contracts and its supporting documents to maintain a checklist of required documents for each of the transaction to serve as a guide and to facilitate completeness of the documents submitted to COA for review and;

Submit the lacking documents enumerated in Annex J of this AAR.

We have recommended that management seeking assistance from the Office of the Sangguniang Bayan, and the Municipal Engineer for possible amendment on the revenue ordinance to comply with ACEL Rates;

Requiring the Municipal Collectors to demand a duly approved Requisition Slip and before processing rental payments;

Directing the Municipal Engineer and, or the GSO to conduct pre and post-inspection for every lease transaction;

Requiring the GSO and MTO to verify details of trip tickets vis-à-vis the amount paid and require the contractor for payment of deficiencies, if there’s any;

Instructing the MTO to maintain custody of equipment keys; and

Instructing concerned offices to maintain equipment logbooks.

We have recommended that management require the Accounting Office to record first the purchases of drugs and medicines and medical, dental and laboratory supplies as inventory;
Require the RHU Inventory In-Charge to submit the monthly report of issuances to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the recording of expenses for inventories consumed or distributed; and
Direct the RHU Inventory In-Charge to prepare and update the stock cards regularly and reconcile it with the results of physical inventory count at least on a semestral basis.

